Hey there! We're adding some protocol features and sprinting on a v1 for the higherrrrrrr protocol. 

The plan is to move out of alpha in the coming weeks.

Here's the current protocol source: https://github.com/Thrive-Point-Group/higherrrrrrr-protocol

Bugs we need to fix: 
- We didn't unit test the display amounts on the decimals on the ETH amount on the NFTs :( this needs to be fixed. 

Features we want to add: 
- Token type enum to a higherrrrrrr token ("regular" ie a regular meme coin, "text_evolution", "image_evolution") - depending on which enum is selected in the token creation, the token will behave differently
- Support for image uri evolutions in the protocol 

Deliverables: 
- Working source in a PR to the OSS 
- Audit through Almanax (DM me for info on this)

Expect the diff for this to be 100-200 lines, so not a huge change. 

Bonus points if you're a student or younger developer looking to get involved. 

Thanks! 
Carl

Clanker uses one sided liquidity in uniswap v3.

So when the pool is created, there is no ETH, just 100% supply of the newly created token. So no real dollars are put in to start.

But how it has a $30k marketcap is that the one sided liquidity is priced so that to buy the tokens you have to buy them at the set price.

For example, say there is 1 million tokens. Each token would be set at $0.03 to start so the market cap is $30k.

You could almost think of it in terms of NFTs where the mint price of each NFT has a starting price and then trading goes from there.

There's a new meta that spawned from Farcaster that I like to call "zk coins". These are coins that give holders the ability to anonymously post from a shared Farcaster account by proving they meet a particular requirement without revealing anything about their identity. This is done using zero-knowledge proofs that "enable one party to prove to another party that a given statement is true without revealing any information beyond the mere fact of the statement's truth" (wikipedia). The three zk projects launched from Farcaster each use zk proofs in interesting ways. Anon Cast and Anonymous Dolphin use zk proofs to verify token balances and 33bit uses them to verify your Farcaster ID is less than a certain number.

Seeing some confusion about scores. A few things to note:

1/ 

1. Scores are not evenly distributed, higher scores are increasingly difficult to get. No one would expect everyone with access to credit to have a perfect 850 credit score. Same with social scores. For developers, we recommend starting with a threshold between 0.5-0.6 and moving up/down as needed.

2. If you're building with scores, there's no need to set a super high threshold. That artificially reduces the number of users who can interact with your product. Imagine only giving loans to people with 850 credit score, pretty much no one would have access to credit.

3. Only 27k+ users have scores 0.7 or higher at this time, the protocol has 800k+ users. There's really no need to worry about a low scores unless you're actually in the bottom digits. You can see a live dashboard of the distribution here: https://bit.ly/3ZQItzH. We are working on model improvements and we expect more users to move up the score ladder.

Builders who choose a single wallet-chain ecosystem will get more distribution, support, funding & even possibly preferential tx execution than builders who choose to try to go multi platform.

We saw glimpses of this with web3 social. The social apps that aggregated rather than betting one protocol were both less liked by the tribal users of individual protocols, and also less promoted by the protocols themselves.

> How does it work under the hood?

It's entirely AI generated‚Äîno input from me. Every game is created from a single GPT prompt, which generates the theme, questions, and answers.
 
To check if a guess is "close enough" to an answer, I prompt GPT to return 20 alternate phrasings, conjugations, categories etc for each answer and then vectorize each. Every time you guess, I check the guess against those vectors to find a sufficiently similar answer or alternate.

couple insights from now having launched multiple mini app flows:

- way larger opportunity than most see, in large part because you can auto auth
- that said, for read/write flows, there needs to be iteration on how identity is exposed
- mini apps need to load way, way faster in WC. telegram is so much faster
- for other builders, best to think of them as extensions of frames rather than full apps. they are still ephemeral / discovery based and that is both a super power as well as a crutch.
- deep linking from mini apps to the rest of WC needs to be way stronger. example: tapping a link to a cast inside a mini app takes you to a logged out wc page inside that mini app, rather than the full cast view.

Stream of consciousness on channels

1. The overwhelming top complaint about the new channels is ‚ÄúI lost access‚Äù / ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt cast in the channels I used to‚Äù

2. The root of this is channels ran for a year as public topics / hashtags and we nudged people to cast in channels for a minor distribution boost.

3. When we launched channels last year, one of the fears was people wouldn‚Äôt cast in channels, since Twitter has tried versions of this and people were too used to casting on main / in the home timeline. 

4. Farcaster user behavior was more nascent / ‚Äúplastic‚Äù / early adopters. So we ended up getting most people to cast in channels.

5. The other reality is most people want to maximize distribution. So telling them ‚Äúchannels = more distribution‚Äù is hard to unlearn, esp. if you‚Äôre more of a weekly active user.

We‚Äôre super lucky to have Christian who is a fantastic event organizer; just naturally brings people together.

I‚Äôm personally very grateful that this being my third Farcaster meetup was not just with magic internet friends but local neighbors ü•π

The signals that tend to do very well fall into one of three categories: 

1. Graph based -- spammers often share similar patterns of activity which can be used to catch them

3. Textual - the content of their casts is often very predictive of their quality

One question people ask me often is "why haven't you expanded out of farcaster yet"?

Focus. Focus is a superpower, because we can only do a few things really well. Designing for all platforms from the start, especially before PMF, is the opposite of focus, bc each one comes with a different set of trade-offs, surface areas, and users.

Instead, my strategy is to build an insanely great product on one platform, nail the core value prop, and then expand outward based on where my customers' audiences are.
